    id: 'p29',
    title: 'Plate Tectonics and Continental Drift',
    content: 'The theory of plate tectonics, which revolutionized geology in the 1960s, describes the Earth\'s lithosphere as divided into several large plates that move relative to one another atop the asthenosphere. This theory unified earlier observations about continental drift, first proposed by Alfred Wegener in 1912, with new evidence from paleomagnetism and seafloor spreading. Wegener had noted the remarkable fit of South America\'s east coast with Africa\'s west coast and cited fossil evidence of identical species found on separated continents. However, his theory was dismissed because he could not explain the mechanism. The discovery of mid-ocean ridges and magnetic striping on the seafloor provided the missing mechanism: new oceanic crust forms at divergent boundaries, pushing older crust outward. There are three types of plate boundaries: divergent (plates moving apart, creating new crust), convergent (plates colliding, causing subduction or mountain building), and transform (plates sliding past each other). Most earthquakes and volcanic eruptions occur along these boundaries. The San Andreas Fault in California is a transform boundary between the Pacific and North American plates. The Himalayas continue to rise as the Indian plate collides with the Eurasian plate.',
