    id: 'p30',
    title: 'The History of the Printing Press',
    content: 'The invention of the movable-type printing press by Johannes Gutenberg around 1440 is widely regarded as one of the most transformative innovations in human history. While printing existed earlier in East Asia using woodblocks, Gutenberg\'s press mechanized the process, making it dramatically faster and cheaper. His invention combined existing technologies—the screw press, oil-based ink, and movable metal type—into a revolutionary system. The Gutenberg Bible, printed around 1455, demonstrated the press\'s capabilities. Within fifty years, printing presses operated throughout Europe, producing an estimated 20 million volumes. The printing press had profound social consequences. It facilitated the Protestant Reformation by enabling widespread distribution of Martin Luther\'s theses. It standardized languages and contributed to the rise of national identity. It democratized knowledge, allowing scientists, philosophers, and artists to share ideas across borders. The rapid dissemination of new ideas accelerated the Scientific Revolution and the Enlightenment. However, the printing press also enabled the spread of misinformation and propaganda, a concern that resonates in today\'s digital age. The parallel between the printing revolution and the modern digital revolution is frequently drawn, as both technologies fundamentally altered how information is created, distributed, and consumed.',
    source: "Barron's",
    difficulty: 'easy',
    questions: ['q_verbal_420', 'q_verbal_421', 'q_verbal_422', 'q_verbal_423', 'q_verbal_424', 'q_verbal_425'],
